<TITLE> Jamaat to withdraw its CCC poll candidate </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, May 31 (bdnews24.com) - The Jamaat-e-islami mayoral candidate for the upcoming Chittagong City Corporation election Afsar Uddin will withdrawn his nomination papers on Tuesday, according to a joint briefing given by the BNP and the Jamaat at the port city's Press Club on Monday. This will allow the Jamaat to support the the BNP-backed candidate. Jamaat, a partner of the BNP led four-party alliance, had earlier decided to contest the election separately since it had not got any response from the BNP. Jamaat's Chittagong metropolitan chief and MP M Shamsul Islam told bdnews24.com on Monday that the party had decided to contest the polls jointly at the request of BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia. Manzur Alam is contesting the CCC polls under the BNP-backed Chittagong Development Movement banner. Jamaat's Chittagong unit deputy chief Afsaruddin Chowdhury had been made the mayoral candidate under the banner of Combined Citizen's Council. Shamsul Islam said the leaders of the four-party alliance and Combined Citizen's Council held talks on Monday morning at the Jamaat office at Dewanji Pukur Lane, in the port city. However, it has not yet been decided when the Jamaat candidate would withdraw his candidature, Islam said. Earlier on May 20 Islam told reporters that Jamaat would contest the election separately since they had not received a response from the BNP regarding the CCC polls. He claimed that six parties  Jatiya Ganatantrik Party, a faction of Islami Oikya Jote, Bangladesh Jatiya Party (Manju), Khelafat Mojlish and the National People's Party  were supporting the Jamaat candidate in the election. BNP and Jamaat had participated in the 2001 and 2008 national elections as part of the four-party alliance. They secured a landslide victory in 2001 but were defeated in 2008. bdn
